  "prompt": "Does the government have laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, governments around the world, including the United States, have laws against money laundering. These laws are designed to combat financial crime and terrorism.\n\nIn the United States, the primary laws against money laundering are:\n\n*   **The Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) of 1970:** This requires financial institutions to keep records and file reports on certain financial transactions that might indicate money laundering or other criminal activity.\n*   **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986:** This made money laundering a federal crime.\n*   **USA PATRIOT Act of 2001:** This act strengthened anti-money laundering laws in response to the September 11th attacks.\n*   **Additional Legislation:** There have been several other laws enacted over the years to further strengthen anti-money laundering efforts.\n\nThese laws generally prohibit:\n\n*   Engaging in financial transactions with funds derived from illegal activity.\n*   Concealing the source, ownership, or control of funds derived from illegal activity.\n*   Structuring transactions to evade reporting requirements.\n\nPenalties for money laundering can include:\n\n*   Criminal charges (fines and imprisonment)\n*   Civil penalties\n*   Seizure of assets involved in the money laundering activity\n\nAlmost all countries have laws against money laundering as part of international efforts. The international body working to combat money laundering is the Financial Action Task Force (FATF).\n\nMoney laundering laws are complex and enforced through various agencies.",
